I don&#39;t know if other people have this problem or not,
but I&#39;ve used Mike Clark&#39;s JWhich to debug some classpath
problems with my Ant scripts. I typically build explicit
classpaths in my ant scripts (usually out of properties
defined in runlib.properties).

This is especially handy in EJB testing where sometimes
the JRE I use is important {BAD WebSphere!, bad, bad!},
so I put a JWhich target that takes in a property (findclass)
that I can pass in on the command line. Here I&#39;ve defaulted
it to finding JWhich (not typically useful).

[The following file is ONLY the JWhich target]

------------- JWhich.xml ------------------------
&lt;project name=&quot;JWhich&quot; default=&quot;JWhich&quot; basedir=&quot;.&quot;&gt;

&lt;property name=&quot;findclass&quot; value=&quot;JWhich&quot;/&gt;

&lt;!-- ========================================= --&gt;
&lt;!-- Defines the classpath used for running.   --&gt;
&lt;!-- ========================================= --&gt;
&lt;path id=&quot;base.classpath&quot;&gt;
    &lt;pathelement path=&quot;${java.class.path}&quot; /&gt;
    &lt;!-- Put the location of JWhich in the classpath --&gt;
    &lt;pathelement location=&quot;C:/junit3.7&quot; /&gt;
&lt;/path&gt;

&lt;target name=&quot;JWhich&quot; description=&quot;Determine where given class is&quot;&gt;
  &lt;java classname=&quot;JWhich&quot;
      fork=&quot;yes&quot;&gt;
      &lt;classpath&gt;
        &lt;path refid=&quot;base.classpath&quot; /&gt;
      &lt;/classpath&gt;
      &lt;arg value=&quot;${findclass}&quot;/&gt;
  &lt;/java&gt;
&lt;/target&gt;

&lt;/project&gt;
